text: Those of you who work in a topic cluster/pillar page model -- do you create the pillar or the cluster content first? Which method have you found to be the most successful?

elements.text: Those of you who work in a topic cluster/pillar page model -- do you create the pillar or the cluster content first? Which method have you found to be the most successful?

text:
The pillar page is often literally the parent page in the URL path, so it often has to exist first.

EG
/topic/
/topic/subtopics/

But we've done hubs where the child pages are all blog posts or articles, and the hub is simply an umbrella page that links to those articles in another directory. That is a decent way to do it if you're not trying to get them into a static URL cluster (mostly a CMS & UX consideration more than a performance consideration).

EG
/topic/
/articles/subtopics/

text:
<@U01HEQWRG0G> I think Google can certainly use subfolder as one way to determine relevance of the content, but, it can be accomplished through internal linking as well. I personally like having things in one subfolder for site analytics and UX, but, it can come at the expense of removing that content from normal feed of content, adding some overhead to maintaining that 'separate' content, etc.

I've written about content hub structures before at <https://www.contentharmony.com/blog/content-hubs/> - might be helpful in figuring out how you want to structure it. Page count and page templates are the biggest deciding factors for me, with some added input from the keyword research.
